  "synthesis": {
    "polymerization_type": null,
    "common_monomers": [],
    "catalysts": [
      "carbon disulfide (xanthation agent)"
    ],
    "industrial_process_notes": "Cellulose (from wood, cotton, hemp, or other organic fibers) is dissolved via the viscose process (alkali + carbon disulfide) and extruded through a slit into a dilute sulfuric acid / sodium sulfate bath, reconverting the viscose into solid cellulose film. Subsequent steps remove residual sulfur, bleach the film, and add glycerin as a softening agent to prevent brittleness. Jacques E. Brandenberger invented cellophane in 1908 and patented it in 1912; DuPont's 1927 nitrocellulose-lacquer moisture-proof coating made it commercially viable for packaging.",
